. Difference between JUnit 4 and JUnit 5
•	JUnit is a testing framework for Java.

JUnit 4	JUnit 5
Monolithic architecture	Modular architecture
Uses older annotations (@Before, @After)	Uses new annotations (@BeforeEach, @AfterEach)
Limited features	More powerful and flexible
No support for Java 8 features	Supports Java 8+ (lambdas, streams)
Less extensible	Highly extensible with extensions

Conclusion: JUnit 5 is more advanced, flexible, and modern compared to JUnit 4


2. JUnit Annotations + Assert Methods
Annotations:
•	@Test – defines test method 
•	@BeforeEach – runs before each test 
•	@AfterEach – runs after each test 
•	@BeforeAll – runs once before all tests 
•	@AfterAll – runs once after all tests 
•	@Disabled – skips test 
Assert Methods:
•	assertEquals(expected, actual) 
•	assertTrue(condition) 
•	assertFalse(condition) 
•	assertNull(object) 
•	assertNotNull(object) 
•	assertThrows() 
Conclusion: Annotations control execution, assertions validate results.

3. JaCoCo and Report Generation
JaCoCo (Java Code Coverage) is a tool used to measure how much of the source code is tested by test cases.
It helps developers identify:
•	Untested code 
•	Weak test coverage 
•	Missing test cases 
Steps to generate report:
1.	Add JaCoCo plugin in Maven/Gradle 
2.	Run test cases using mvn test 
3.	Generate coverage report using mvn jacoco:report 
4.	Open HTML report to view coverage 
The report shows:
•	Line coverage 
•	Branch coverage 
•	Method coverage 
Conclusion: JaCoCo improves code quality by ensuring maximum test coverage.

4. Docker Architecture and Components
Docker is a containerization platform with a client-server architecture.
Components:
•	Docker Client: Interface where users run commands 
•	Docker Daemon: Background service that manages containers 
•	Docker Images: Templates used to create containers 
•	Docker Containers: Running instances of images 
•	Docker Registry (Docker Hub): Stores and distributes images 
Working:
Client sends commands → Daemon processes → Containers are created from images.
Conclusion: Docker architecture enables fast and efficient application deployment.


5. Docker Image, Dockerfile, Docker Hub
Docker uses three key elements:
•	Docker Image: A read-only template containing application code and dependencies. It is used to create containers. 
•	Dockerfile: A text file containing instructions (like install software, copy files) to build an image. 
•	Docker Hub: A cloud-based repository to store, share, and download Docker images. 
Working:
Dockerfile → builds Image → Image runs as Container → stored in Docker Hub
Conclusion: These components simplify application packaging and deployment.

6.Virtuilaztion and containeriztaion



Virtualization and containerization are techniques to run multiple applications.
•	Virtualization uses a hypervisor to create virtual machines, each with its own OS. 
•	Containerization uses the host OS kernel to run lightweight containers. 
Differences:
•	Virtual machines are heavy and slow 
•	Containers are lightweight and fast 
•	VMs require full OS, containers share OS 
•	Containers provide better performance 
Conclusion: Containerization is more efficient and widely used in DevOps.



7. Lifecycle of Docker Container
Docker containers go through different stages:
1.	Create – container is created from image 
2.	Start – container starts execution 
3.	Run – application runs inside container 
4.	Pause – container is temporarily stopped 
5.	Stop – container execution stops 
6.	Remove – container is deleted 
These stages help manage application lifecycle efficiently.
Conclusion: Understanding lifecycle helps in better container management.

