3. Docker Commands (Start, Stop, Kill)
Docker provides commands to manage container lifecycle.
Definition:
Docker commands control the execution of containers.
Commands:
•	Start 
 
docker start <container_id>
 
Starts an already created container.
•	Stop 
 
docker stop <container_id>
 
Stops container gracefully.
•	Kill 
 
docker kill <container_id>
 
Stops container immediately (forcefully).
Differences:
•	Stop → allows cleanup 
•	Kill → immediate termination 
Importance:
•	Helps manage running applications 
•	Enables resource control 
Conclusion: These commands are essential for efficient container management in Docker.

4. Purpose of Volume in Docker
Docker volume is used for data storage and persistence.
Definition:
A volume is a storage mechanism that allows data to exist outside the container.
Features:
•	Data persists even after container deletion 
•	Can be shared between multiple containers 
•	Stored on host system 
Usage:
 
docker run -v /host:/container
 
Advantages:
•	Data backup and recovery 
•	Improved performance 
•	Easy data sharing 
Example:
Database data stored in volume remains even if container stops.
Conclusion: Docker volumes ensure safe and persistent data storage across containers.

5. Puppet Architecture (Master–Agent)




Puppet is a configuration management tool used to automate system setup.
Components:
•	Puppet Master: Central server storing configurations 
•	Puppet Agent: Installed on client machines 
•	Nodes: Systems being managed 
Working:
1.	Agent requests configuration from Master 
2.	Master sends configuration (manifest) 
3.	Agent applies configuration to system 
Features:
•	Automation 
•	Centralized control 
•	Consistency 
Advantages:
•	Reduces manual work 
•	Ensures uniform configuration 
Conclusion: Puppet Master–Agent architecture enables automated and consistent system management.

